NYC Open Data FOIL Denial Analysis
Tools: Python · pandas
Data: NYC Open Data — Agency Open Data Plans (live city dataset)
Overview
Analysis of NYC agency responses to Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) requests, focusing on datasets that agencies have refused to publish on the Open Data portal. By cross-referencing FOIL request volume against denial justifications, this project maps where public demand for government data is highest — and where agencies are pushing back most.
Key Findings
DEP's hazardous materials database is the single most-requested denied dataset.
The DERTA/IPS Database — containing hazardous materials storage information — generated 1,081 FOIL requests while remaining off the Open Data portal, justified by the agency as a security risk. This is more than three times the request volume of the next most-denied dataset.
"Security" and "privacy" are the dominant justification categories.
Denial reasons cluster into a small number of categories: security risk, personally identifiable information (PII), internal administration, and administrative burden. PII concerns are cited most frequently across agencies, often for datasets where redaction would be technically feasible.
The NYPD and OATH account for a disproportionate share of denials by volume.
NYPD denials include gun recovery data, investigative cards, and ShotSpotter activation records — all citing either machine-readability limitations or law enforcement sensitivity. OATH generated a large number of individual "Respondent's Data" denial entries, suggesting a pattern of treating routine payment records as exempt from publication.
Some agencies cite backlog rather than sensitivity.
The Department of Buildings repeatedly justifies non-publication with "other datasets have been prioritized" — a capacity argument rather than a legal one. This represents a distinct and trackable denial category: datasets that could be published but haven't been.
A meaningful percentage of all tracked datasets are not on the Open Data plan.
Calculated as denied / total, this figure provides a baseline transparency rate for NYC's Open Data program across all participating agencies.
Denial Categories (Derived)
